02 18:00:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
{"id":"astro-ph/0203240","submitter":"Brian D. Fields","authors":"Richard H. Cyburt, Brian D. Fields, Vasiliki Pavlidou, Benjamin D.\n  Wandelt (UIUC)","title":"Constraining Strong Baryon-Dark Matter Interactions with Primordial\n  Nucleosynthesis and Cosmic Rays","comments":"17 pages, 2 figures; plain LaTeX. To appear in PRD","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev. D65 (2002) 123503","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.65.123503","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Self-interacting dark matter (SIDM) was introduced by Spergel & Steinhardt to\naddress possible discrepancies between collisionless dark matter simulations\nand observations on scales of less than 1 Mpc. We examine the case in which\ndark matter particles not only have strong self-interactions but also have\nstrong interactions with baryons. The presence of such interactions will have\ndirect implications for nuclear and particle astrophysics. Among these are a\nchange in the predicted abundances from big bang nucleosynthesis (BBN) and the\nflux of gamma-rays produced by the decay of neutral pions which originate in\ncollisions between dark matter and Galactic cosmic rays (CR). From these\neffects we constrain the strength of the baryon--dark matter interactions\nthrough the ratio of baryon - dark matter interaction cross section to dark\nmatter mass, $s$. We find that BBN places a weak upper limit to this ratio $<\n10^8 cm^2/g$. CR-SIDM interactions, however, limit the possible DM-baryon cross\nsection to $< 5 \\times 10^{-3} cm^2/g$; this rules out an energy-independent\ninteraction, but not one which falls with center-of-mass velocity as $s \\propto\n1/v$ or steeper.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 14 Mar 2002 21:05:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
