{"id":"math/0203147","submitter":"Masanori Asakura","authors":"Masanori Asakura and Shuji Saito","title":"Generalized Jacobian Rings for Open Complete Intersections","comments":"33pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AG","license":null,"abstract":"  In this paper, we develop the theory of Jacobian rings of open complete\nintersections, which mean a pair $(X,Z)$ where $X$ is a smooth complete\nintersection in the projective space and and $Z$ is a simple normal crossing\ndivisor in $X$ whose irreducible components are smooth hypersurface sections on\n$X$. Our Jacobian rings give an algebraic description of the cohomology of the\nopen complement $X-Z$ and it is a natural generalization of the Poincar\\'e\nresidue representation of the cohomology of a hypersurface originally invented\nby Griffiths. The main results generalize the Macaulay's duality theorem and\nthe Donagi's symmetrizer lemma for usual Jacobian rings for hypersurfaces. A\nfeature that distinguishes our generalized Jacobian rings from usual ones is\nthat there are instances where duality fails to be perfect while the defect can\nbe controlled explicitly by using the defining equations of $Z$ in $X$. Two\napplications of the main results are given: One is the infinitesimal Torelli\nproblem for open complete intersections. Another is an explicit bound for\nNori's connectivity in case of complete intersections. The results have been\napplied also to study of algebraic cycles in several other works.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 15 Mar 2002 07:08:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
